{{main|Honda Sports Award}}
The '''Honda Sports Award''' for basketball is presented annually to the best [[women's college basketball]] player, as selected by a panel of more than 1,000 [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] administrators. The award was first presented following the 1976‚Äì77 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's College Basketball Awards (2016‚Äì17)|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/w_basketball_RB/2017/Awards.pdf|website=ncaa.org|publisher=NCAA|page=15|accessdate=February 13, 2017|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Past Honda Sports Award Winners for Basketball|url=http://www.collegiatewomensportsawards.com/archives/basketball|website=collegiatewomensportsawards.com|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Four nominees are chosen annually by a panel of coaches representing the [[Women's Basketball Coaches Association]] (WBCA), and the winner is chosen by the votes of administrators from every NCAA member institution, with each institution having one vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nominees Announced for 2015-16 Honda Sport Award for Women‚Äôs Basketball|url=http://collegiatewomensportsawards.com/releases/2015-16/20160404wbbnoms|website=collegiatewomensportsawards.com|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>
==Winners==
Thirty women's college basketball players have received the Honda Sports Award for basketball in the 40 seasons it has been presented. Nine players have won the award multiple times. [[Breanna Stewart]] of [[Connecticut Huskies women's basketball|Connecticut]] is the only three-time winner; eight others have won the award twice: [[Nancy Lieberman]] of [[Old Dominion Lady Monarchs basketball|Old Dominion]], [[Cheryl Miller]] of [[USC Trojans women's basketball|Southern California]], [[Dawn Staley]] of [[Virginia Cavaliers|Virginia]], [[Chamique Holdsclaw]] of [[Tennessee Lady Volunteers basketball|Tennessee]], [[Diana Taurasi]] of Connecticut, [[Seimone Augustus]] of [[LSU Lady Tigers basketball|LSU]], [[Candace Parker]] of Tennessee, and [[Maya Moore]] of Connecticut.
